title: Add past state support in Attention Op for GPT-2
body:
**Description**: 

Update Attention op to support past  state. 

The past state is the hidden state for K and V with shape (2, B, N, S', H), where S' is the sequence length for past state. The output of present state will be (2, B, N, S*, H) where S* = S' + S, and S is the sequence length for current input_ids.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

Current Attention does not support past state input and output. GPT2 model need past state to speed up decoding.

title: Discover trainable parameters using reverse DFS from loss node
body:
**Description**: 
Discover trainable parameters using reverse DFS from loss node, omitting recursion along untrainable inputs.

_Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?_
The existing discovery process for trainable parameters assumes all initializers are trainable unless they they match a particular node op type and input index. This can fail to detect that an otherwise trainable parameter is blocked by a non-trainable parameter. For example, consider a => b => c. If c is trainable and b is non trainable, then this implies a is also not trainable.

The user can inspect the found list of trainable parameters with `TrainingSession::GetWeights()`

title: fix build: pin pipeline Node.js version to 12.16.3
body:
pin Node.js version to 12.16.3 to fix build break.

This is a quick fix to unblock the build pipeline. There will be a complete fix to enable pipeline work with latest Node.js LTS.

why it broke the build?
- since 12.17, NAPI v6 is officially supported and the old macro `NAPI_EXPERIMENT` is removed and replaced by `NAPI_VERSION` 6. This cause the node.js binding to fail the build.

why not using NAPI v6?
- NAPI v6 is a very new API version so that onnxruntime would not work on some old Node.js version. **We are not really using any v6 features that implemented in Node.js recently.** The only feature we used in v6 is BigInt, which is already supported in Node.js 2 years ago. (the reason why BigInt is added in v6 is another story)

can current node.js binding work on latest and future Node.js without any code change?
- YES, it can. In our case, the NAPI v6 release only affect the typed array element type definition in `napi.h`. As explained above, the node.js already supported bigint 2 years ago and bigint64/biguint64 is already supported since then.

what is the plan for a complete fix?
- The goal is to make nodejs binding work with both old/new `napi.h` without declare the binding it self requires NAPI v6. This is kind of tricky but we want to support the current major node.js version. Details is still to be figured out.

title: Enable BiasGelu fusion for training
body:
**Description**
Add gradient for BiasGelu and FastGelu with bias. Enable BiasGelu fusion transformer in TrainingSession.

**Motivation and Context**
Enable BiasGelu fusion to improve performance.


# Performance test
Baseline (9e3b5c62fbb4db01b26ffd0947d2fe4c9ca0376c)
Updated (GELU approximation and bias GELU fusion) (06e8142d29f7e30cb730024cda4a26b8d5a6546b)

## Kernel Benchmark

```
nvprof --print-gpu-summary ./onnxruntime_training_bert --model_name /bert_ort/bert_models/nv/bert-large/bert-large-uncased_L_24_H_1024_A_16_V_30528_S_512_Dp_0.1_optimized_layer_norm --train_data_dir /bert_data/128/books_wiki_en_corpus/train --test_data_dir /bert_data/128/books_wiki_en_corpus/test --train_batch_size 32 --mode train --num_train_steps 100 --display_loss_steps 1 --warmup_ratio=0.2843 --warmup_mode=Poly --optimizer lamb --gradient_accumulation_steps 1 --max_predictions_per_seq=20 --use_nccl --use_mixed_precision --allreduce_in_fp16
```

### Baseline
```
Time(%)      Time     Calls       Avg       Min       Max  Name
  2.29%  454.59ms      2500  181.84us  52.160us  196.57us  [GELU grad] void onnxruntime::cuda::_BinaryElementWiseSimple<bool=1, bool=1, __half, __half, onnxruntime::cuda::OP_GeluGrad<__half>, int=256, int=4>(__half const *, __half const *, onnxruntime::cuda::_BinaryElementWiseSimple<bool=1, bool=1, __half, __half, onnxruntime::cuda::OP_GeluGrad<__half>, int=256, int=4>*, __half const &, int)

  1.76%  349.01ms      2500  139.60us  37.376us  152.29us  [GELU] void onnxruntime::cuda::_UnaryElementWise<__half, __half, onnxruntime::contrib::cuda::OP_Gelu<__half>, int=256, int=4>(__half const *, __half*, __half, int)

  1.07%  211.47ms      2500  84.587us  23.680us  89.855us  [Add bias] void onnxruntime::cuda::_BinaryElementWise<__half, __half, onnxruntime::cuda::OP_Add<__half, __half>, bool=1, bool=0, int=256, int=4>(int, onnxruntime::cuda::TArray<long, int=8>, __half const *, onnxruntime::cuda::TArray, __half const *, onnxruntime::cuda::_BinaryElementWise<__half, __half<onnxruntime::cuda::fast_divmod, int=8>, onnxruntime::cuda::OP_Add<__half, __half>, bool=1, bool=0, int=256, int=4>, onnxruntime::cuda::TArray<long, int=8>*, __half const &, int)
```

### Updated
```
Time(%)      Time     Calls       Avg       Min       Max  Name
  1.69%  328.94ms      2500  131.58us  44.928us  140.86us  [Fast GELU grad] void onnxruntime::cuda::BiasGeluGradDxKernel<__half, onnxruntime::gelu_computation_mode::Approximation, int=4, int=4>(long, __half const *, __half const , __half const , onnxruntime::cuda::BiasGeluGradDxKernel<__half, onnxruntime::gelu_computation_mode::Approximation, int=4, int=4>*)

  1.25%  241.84ms      2500  96.735us  26.912us  104.99us  [Add bias and fast GELU] void onnxruntime::contrib::cuda::FastGeluKernel2<unsigned int=256>(__half2, onnxruntime::contrib::cuda::FastGeluKernel2<unsigned int=256>, onnxruntime::contrib::cuda::FastGeluKernel2<unsigned int=256>, int, int, onnxruntime::contrib::cuda::FastGeluKernel2<unsigned int=256> const *, onnxruntime::contrib::cuda::FastGeluKernel2<unsigned int=256> const , onnxruntime::contrib::cuda::FastGeluKernel2<unsigned int=256>*)
```

title: MLAS: change quantized GEMM to parameter struct
body:
**Description**: The quantized GEMM routine has changed from taking tons of parameters to a structure containing the same parameters.

**Motivation and Context**:
In order to improve fusions with the core of the quantized GEMM, more parameters are going to be needed. Instead of adding more function wrappers, move all of the parameters to a structure instead. This PR does the initial transform of the existing parameters.

One immediate benefit of the new scheme is that it makes it easier to use a single kernel for MatMulInteger that handles u8u8 and u8s8. The same could also be done for the quantized attention op too.

The outer loops of the quantized GEMM have been templatized to avoid nasty cut/paste of these loops for the various architectures.

Also fixed the quantized attention test to disable the tests on platforms that don't have a MLAS quantized GEMM available. This fixes failing tests seen on ARM64 builds.

title: Handle corner case in Resize op
body:
**Description**: Handle a corner case in the resize operator where-in an input dim (and the corresponding output dim) could be 0 and proceeding to divide the output dim by the input dim to compute the scale for the dimension results in a NaN.  There are some cases where-in a dimension can be legitimately zero (zero bounding boxes in an object detection model, no keypoints extractable from an image, etc.) and the resize op needs to be able to handle this.

**Motivation and Context**
Noticed while debugging a model run failure.

title: Fix subgraph based reshape fusion
body:
**Description**: #3931 added a new pattern for reshape fusion (Concat <-- subgraph <--root) by adding a shape value  of `-1` to the shape initializer for this pattern. The checks before triggering this optimization pass need to be stricter. This can only be done when the it is firmly established that the subgraph's output contains **only one element**. This broke a 1PP model wherein a Shape node was feeding into the Concat. The Shape node would have produced multi-element data that was substituted with a `-1` and thus it tampered with the rank of the reshaped tensor when the Reshape was actually computed and broke downstream nodes.

**Motivation and Context**
Fix 1PP model

title: Add PytorchTrainerOptions class for the new pytorch frontend
body:
The new frontend will take dependency on a schema validation library called 'cerberus'
This class will hold all optional parameters for the python frontend and performs strict schema and type validation

It returns an immutable object that allows accessing configurations in an object-like way, such as `is_enabled=options.mixed_precision.enabled`, `steps=options.batch.gradient_accumulation_steps`

When this class is printed, it shows a dictionary representation of the options being stored. default values are supported out of the box

The new frontend will also introduce two new submodules: `onnxruntime.capi.training.optim` and `onnxruntime.capi.training.amp`

Unit tests are integrated into the CI

title: Fix TensorRT memory leaks
body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.

Instead of passing a raw pointer inside `struct TensorrtFuncState`, I'm passing a pointer to a unique_pointer class. This concerns variables `context` and `engine`. This way we can call `destroy` method inside `compute_func` in case there's a change update and the engine needs to be recreated. The call to `destroy` is made indirectly using `reset` method of unique_pointer. The order in which `reset` is being called is important, if violated TensorRT explodes. 



**Motivation and Context**

This change is required in order to resolve the memory leak issues that arise when the TensorRT provider re-creates an engine due to input size change. 
I'm not aware of an open issue for this.

title: optimize transpose CUDA kernel
body:
In this PR, the following things are done to improve CUDA transpose kernel. With this PR, the throughput of BERT-L is improved by ~1.4%.

1.  Flatten the adjacent dimensions which are contiguous. For example: permutations[0, 2, 3, 1] -> [0, 2, 1], permutations[0, 3, 1, 2] -> [0, 2, 1]. This will make the loop iterations in transpose kernel less.
2.  For 3D tensor, if the permutations are done in last two dimensions, then we can easily use shared memory to improve GPU memory utilization.
3. For 4D tensor, if the permutations are not done in the last dimension, then we can use int4 to access memory. Besides, if the last two dimensions can fit in block size, then the kernel can be simplified by configuring block size with the shape of last two dimensions.

The table below is the improvement for BERT-L tensor with shape [64, 128, 16, 64]

 | Baseline (micro seconds) | Optimization (micro seconds) | Improvement
-- | -- | -- | --
Permutation: [0 2 3 1] | 110.531 | 95.808 | 13%
Permutation: [0 3 1 2] | 187.981 | 89.6352 | 52%
Permutation: [0 2 1 3] | 87.7408 | 31.0208 | 65%

title: Use OpenMP-like synchronization patterns in Eigen thread pool
body:
**Description**: 

This PR updates the thread pool implementation to make work distribution over the Eigen thread pool more closely resemble techniques used in OpenMP.  In particular: 

(1) A thread entering a parallel loop works on the iterations itself, rather than requiring a thread switch to/from a thread in the pool, if called from outside the thread pool.

(2) To support #1, work items pushed to the thread pool run a loop to claim iterations from a shared counter via atomic-fetch-and-add, as opposed to having work items themselves represent individual batches of iterations.  This means that any thread working on the loop can execute any batch of iterations, including having the main thread run through all of the batches itself if the loop turns out to be short-running. 

(3) As with OpenMP active scheduling, the worker loop spins waiting for work prior to blocking.  This avoids OS blocking / wake-up paths in workloads with series of short-running parallel sections.  The default spinning duration prior to blocking is measured at around 1ms.

Performance tests on a 32-vCPU VM for CPU inference workloads show performance broadly similar to OpenMP builds, with p50 across 143 models a 12% improvement, and p80 a 28% improvement.

**Motivation and Context**

The PR aims to simplify the configuration of threading with ORT by providing consistent performance with OpenMP-based parallelism.

title: NHWC transformation for ACL and ArmNN EPs
body:
NCHWC transformation is tailored for mlas library and does not accomodate
the simpler NHWC format supported by ACL and ArmNN EPs.

Add NHWC transformation with support to reorder input, output and permute
(fused) convolution weights and enable it for ACL and ArmnNN EPs.

With ACL EPs the optimizaiton improves latency for mobilenets_v2 with 33%,
resnet50_v1 with 24% and vgg19 with 64%. Subsequent pacthes with support
for Concat and BN channel-last operations will further improve performance
with ~20%.
